Airline On-Time Performance Data Exploration¶

by Ahmed Awwad¶

Introduction¶

This dataset reports flights in the United States, including carriers, arrival and departure delays, and reasons for delays, from 2005 to 2007

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing attributes for approximately 21,000,000 flight report.

In [6]:
cancel_reson = {'A':'carrier','B':'weather','C':'NAS','D':'security'}
df['CancellationCode'] = df['CancellationCode'].fillna('None')
df['CancelReason'] = df['CancellationCode'].replace(cancel_reson.keys(),cancel_reson.values()).astype('category')

# we will use the iata as a prime key to join the city variable to our dateframe
# we will join for both orgin city and destaintaion city
org = airports[['iata','city']].rename(columns={'iata':'Origin','city':'OriginCity'})
dest = airports[['iata','city']].rename(columns={'iata':'Dest','city':'DestCity'})
df = df.merge(org, on='Origin')
df = df.merge(dest, on='Dest')
df['OriginCity']=df['OriginCity']
df['DestCity']=df['DestCity']
#after finishing we can get rid of the iata code to save more space
df.drop(['Origin','Dest'],axis =1,inplace = True)

we will sum the the delytime to only one column called TotalDelay to save more space also reduce the number of columns

In [10]:
delay = df.loc[:,'CarrierDelay':'LateAircraftDelay']
df['TotalDelay'] = delay.sum(axis =1)
df.drop(delay.columns,axis =1,inplace = True)

as we did for delay time we can also reduce the number of columns of the date and time by using only one column instead of 4 columns make the dateset more readable also to save some memory

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 21,706,733 flight report in the dataset with 11 features (cDate,Cancelled,CancelReason,TotalDelay,ArrDelay DepDelay,ActualElapsedTime,OriginCity,DestCity,Diverted,Distance). some variables are numeric in nature like TotalDely Distance,... , and the variables DestCity, OriginCity,CancelReason are categorical ,also the variables cancelled and Diverted is boolean variables and finally the Date is datetime variable

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out which cities have make more from/to flights and also the reasons for delayed and cancelled flights

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that TotalDelay will help me to figure the most citits with the number of delayed flights also the the range of delyation time for the flights for each city also the Date variable would help me to see the variation during the period from 2005 to 2007 also the Distance will help me to se if there is a relation between delayed and cancelled flights and the distacne between the two ciites finally the CancellReason variable will help me to figure out the most reason for flight cancellations

# first let's choose the flights between only the top 6 citites 
most_flights = df[(df['OriginCity'].isin(top_cities)) &(df['DestCity'].isin(top_cities)) ]
# now let's sort the cities acording to their names
most_flights= most_flights.groupby(['OriginCity','DestCity']).count().sort_values(by= ['OriginCity','DestCity'])['Distance'].reset_index()
most_flights.rename(columns ={'Distance':'NoOfFlights'},inplace= True)
# now let's fix the missed flights so if cities have no flights between itself so we simply put 0 in the number of the flights
mised_citties= most_flights['OriginCity'].value_counts()[(most_flights['OriginCity'].value_counts()<6)].index
for city in mised_citties:
    most_flights.loc[-1] = [city, city, 0]
    most_flights.index = most_flights.index + 1
# now we will resort the cities by their names to be able to reshape the data in the next step
# also we will fix the indexes just to keep our data clean along the way
most_flights = most_flights.sort_values(by= ['OriginCity','DestCity']).reset_index().drop('index',axis =1)
# now we have a dataframe with 36 value that sorted by the city name 
# so name we reshape the data into 6 group for each city
no_of_flights = np.array(most_flights['NoOfFlights']).reshape(6,6)

Conclusions¶

There are 21,706,733 flight report in the dataset with 11 features (cDate,Cancelled,CancelReason,TotalDelay,ArrDelay DepDelay,ActualElapsedTime,OriginCity,DestCity,Diverted,Distance). some variables are numeric in nature like TotalDely Distance,... , and the variables DestCity, OriginCity,CancelReason are categorical ,also the variables cancelled and Diverted is boolean variables and finally the Date is datetime variable

the DestCity variable shows that Chiago has the most number of delyed flights, cancelled flights and also have the most vistied during all the cities

the data is almost nature maybe there are some weird outliers in some variable but it's still acceptable values, but for the countruction of the dataframe we did some cleaning process in order to be able to reduce the number of columns and that will will save more memory in it's turn.

the weather played a big role in cancelled flights as we saw the month january ,December, and febraury have the highest number of cancelled flights due to the bad weather also we found that the largest number of flights between two cities was between Chicago and New York also we see that the number on-ward flights is almost equal to the number of return flights

Chicago is almost the highest of everything has the most number of flights to/from aslo have the highest number of cancelled and delayed flights also the long distances surprisingly tend to be less cancelled or delayed also although Chicago has the highest number of cancelled flights it doesn't have the hightest cancellation ratio
